
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `df` baraye didane fazaye disk-e estefade shode va baghi mande dar system shoma be kar miravad. Yani, disk free ro neshun mide.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `df -h` --> 📏 Namayeshe hajme disk be surate ghabele khandan baraye ensan (kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte).
    🔹 `df -T` --> ℹ️ Namayeshe no'e filesystem (ext4, tmpfs, etc.).
    🔹 `df -i` --> 🔢 Namayeshe tedade inode-haye estefade shode va baghi mande.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ df

    🔹 Namayeshe estandarde fazaye disk.

    $ df -h

    🔹 Namayeshe fazaye disk be surate ghabele khandan.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ df -h /home

    🔹 Namayeshe estefade az disk dar directory `/home` be surate ghabele khandan. In dastoor be shoma komak mikone ke bedunid cheghadr fazaye disk dar pooshe-ye `home` baghi munde.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `df` command is used to display the amount of disk space available and used on your system. Essentially, it shows disk free space.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `df -h` --> 📏 Display disk space in a human-readable format (kilobytes, megabytes, gigabytes).
    🔹 `df -T` --> ℹ️ Display the filesystem type (ext4, tmpfs, etc.).
    🔹 `df -i` --> 🔢 Display the number of inodes used and available.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ df

    🔹 Standard display of disk space usage.

    $ df -h

    🔹 Display disk space in human-readable format.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ df -h /home

    🔹 Display disk usage for the `/home` directory in a human-readable format.  This command helps you quickly see how much disk space is remaining in your `home` folder.
